      <hedline>
        <hl1>Clinton Makes His Last Hurrah</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Grant Perry letter comments on August 11 article on displeasure among Hollywood's entertainment moguls over Vice Pres Al Gore's selection of industry critic, Sen Joseph Lieberman, as his vice presidential running mate; drawing (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Moguls Rattled by Gore's Choice of Critic of Entertainment Industry'' (news article, Aug. 11):  Hollywood moguls may be rattled by Vice President Al Gore's choice of Senator Joseph I. Lieberman to be his running mate, but many Democrats, myself included, are very comfortable with Mr. Lieberman because he has spoken out against the excesses of the entertainment industry.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Moguls Rattled by Gore's Choice of Critic of Entertainment Industry'' (news article, Aug. 11):  Hollywood moguls may be rattled by Vice President Al Gore's choice of Senator Joseph I. Lieberman to be his running mate, but many Democrats, myself included, are very comfortable with Mr. Lieberman because he has spoken out against the excesses of the entertainment industry.</p>
        <p>As usual, Hollywood reacts to its critics by issuing warnings about censorship and ''conflict with the creative process.'' Most of us are pleading for some self-restraint, not censorship.</p>
        <p>Regarding the creative process, the unremitting torrent of what Senator Lieberman has called ''death and degradation'' appears to be much more the product of cynical marketing decisions and formulaic production than of the creative process.</p>
        <p>GRANT PERRY  Ridgefield, Conn., Aug. 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
